rows.description:
Highly expressed junctions from all 803 GTEx v3 muscle samples.
The junction-spanning read counts are normalized to represent the average spanning read count per-sample (see formula below). Only junctions with rounded normalized spanning read count > 0 are included in this track.

average_unique_reads_per_muscle_sample = (total_unqiue_reads_in_all_muscle_samples / number_of_muscle_samples)
per_sample_normalized_read_count = raw_read_count * average_unique_reads_per_muscle_sample / total_unqiue_reads_in_this_sample
normalized read count for junction = sum(per_sample_normalized_read_counts) / number_of_muscle_samples
rows.name: Norm. GTEx Muscle

rows.description:
SpliceAI delta score visualization. This is generated from Illumina's precomputed scores for all possible
SNVs and small InDels within the exons and introns of GENCODE v24 canonical transcripts.
This track shows an arc for each variant that's predicted to disrupt splicing at another nearby position in the mRNA with a score >= 0.5

Gross motor delay, severe weakness (minimal antigravity movements) and absent reflexes. Long term NG/NJ fed. BiPAP since 2 years of age. Muscle biopsy shows a chronic myopathic process with variation in fibre diameters, increased internal nuclei and increased interstitial collagen. The process appears relatively static with no active necrosis or regeneration observed. Electron microscopy reveals frequent minicores with often multiple small localised areas of sarcomeric disruption. No nemaline rods are identified.

There were no concerns about affected female until after her first vaccination. Her head was noted to be floppy immediately after this. She failed to thrive for a period of time but gradually picked up. She then got her 4 month vaccine. Again there was screaming and irritability and she became hypotonic again. Again there was some recovery and then again after the 6 month vaccination, she became screaming, irritable and sleepy.From this time onwards, there was improvement. She walked at 22 months and at school, by 5 years of age,she was able to walk. Year 6 - 8, she was in a wheelchair. In Year 9 she was able to walk and currently she can at least walk 200m. Over long time periods there is a variation in her muscle strength. Some days, she feels tired and finds it difficult to breath and has little energy and there are other days when she feels much better.O/E scoliosis, predominantly prox weakness Her finger flexors are of normal strength. She has bilateral ptosis and mild weakness of eye closure. Poor respiratory function
